@julien-c Because:
1/ It is hard to remember from a user PoV
2/ It is a very bad design practice to have 2 types that maps to the same internal structure/type: we are in a classic case of different constructors for the same type eg:

```js
const port = new Env('NODE_PORT')
const port2 = new Env({name: 'NODE_PORT', type: 'Number', defaultValue: 3000})
```

You would never suggest to me to have 2 ≠ types in JS to achieve this use case (or at least I want to believe you would not).

