Thanks for looking into this issue -- I also saw on the forum that it was a topic of concern for people because private keys are indeed among the most sensitive files that may exist on the server.

@hlieberman, @pde suggested that you might have an idea about the Debian policy aspects of this (or already know of a plan for what our file permissions should be). In particular I'm wondering whether there are many systems where private keys ought to be group-readable, not just owner-readable, because the web server is running as e.g. user `httpd` group `httpd` (or `www`), while the `privkey.pem` might be owned by root. In that case it ought to be group-readable to allow the daemon to read it at startup.

@pde also suggested `440` instead of either `660` or `600` as a default (because there's normally no need to write to the privkey and because it would be helpful to warn people who are trying to delete it!) -- and finding a way to make the file modes configurable in addition to changing the default. (I don't know if there's work toward that in another PR yet.)

