@evanp, I largely agree with you. A number of us have had this conversation internally.

Since our first non-development release of 0.1.0, we've largely treated Certbot like it was 1.0+. We have had stable APIs and spent a lot of time avoiding making breaking changes. Our initial hesitation about calling it 1.0 was that we weren't sure if the software was production ready. Certbot 1.0 was launched the same day as you could obtain trusted certificates from Let's Encrypt so before that it hadn't seen much real world usage. Over the 2+ years since that release, we've been installed and run regularly on millions of web servers and feel much more confident about Certbot's abilities here.

Honestly, the only reason we haven't declared Certbot 1.0 is it's a PR opportunity for us to make noise about Certbot and bring attention to features people have missed since the initial release. We plan to make use of that soon, but thanks for the nudge here and you can feel confident that Certbot's not going to suddenly change it's behavior on you.

